<DOC><DOCNO> AP890922-0200 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1956EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-22 0413</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0423</SECOND><HEAD>Tropical Storm Hugo Poses Threat of Heavy Rain In The Northeast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Hurricane Hugo lost some of its fury as it roared northwardFriday, fading to a tropical storm and then dwindling to an unnamedstorm that nevertheless brought heavy rain and the threat offlooding from Tennessee to New York.   Rainfall totals of 4 to 8 inches were possible in the storm'spath, and forecasters warned that isolated tornadoes were possiblefrom Virginia to Pennsylvania.   The storm produced 6 inches of rain at Savannah, Ga., in 24 hours.   Hurricane Hugo packed winds of 135 mph as it hit the SouthCarolina coast Wednesday night. Its eye passed just east ofCharleston, moved northwest to just west of Sumter and entered NorthCarolina just west of Charlotte.   The strong wind downed thousands of trees, damaged roofs,destroyed homes, blew over signs and bent steel towers to theground. Hugo dumped 3.16 inches of rain in about 12 hours atCharlotte, and during the early morning produced wind to 69 mph withgusts to 87 mph.   Thunderstorms associated with Hugo also produced wind gusts to 60mph at Myrtle Beach, S.C., and wind gusts to 109 mph at Sumter, S.C.At Snowshoe, W.Va., wind Friday gusted to 60 mph.   Tree damage was so extensive in North Carolina that the stateforest service had to be called in to help clear the debris anddowned trees.   Showers and thunderstorms extended from Mississippi and Alabamato the lower Great Lakes region and New York state Friday afternoon.Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 8 a.m. EDTincluded 3 inches at Savannah, Ga., 1 inch at Myrtle Beach, S.C.,and .98 inches at Birmingham, Ala.   Strong northwesterly winds were ushering cold Canadian air intothe north central United States. Showers and thurderstorms werereported over southwest Texas and southern New Mexico.   Forecasters posted flood watches for western Massachusetts andwestern Connecticut and flash flood watches for Vermont and easternNew York state. They posted overnight freeze warnings for Minnesota,South Dakota, northwest Iowa and northern and west-central Wisconsin.   The cold spot in the nation Friday was West Yellowstone, Mont.,with a low of 26 degrees.   Afternoon temperatures were warming into the 80s across thesouthern Atlantic Coast and from south-central Texas through easternTexas to the central Gulf Coast; in the 90s in the desert Southwest;in the 40s across the Dakotas, eastern Montana and northernMinnesota.</TEXT></DOC>